      "text": "Ahab wants the haiku version rebuilt to be less explanatory, more visceral\u2014less TED talk, more pure emotion/image without the explanation wrapper. He wants it dark, weird, with bite. \n\nSo the haiku prompt needs to strip back the exposition and just... be the haiku. Raw, strange, hitting hard. Let me rebuild this to be sharper, less \"here's what this means\" and more \"here's the thing itself.\"\n\nLet me think about what makes a haiku prompt actually *work*:\n- No preamble about what we're doing\n- No explanation of the emotional stakes\n- Just the image/moment/sensation\n- Weird specificity\n- Dark or unsettling undertone\n- Let the reader find their own meaning\n\nThis is a shift from \"here's the concept of loneliness, now haiku it\" to something more like \"here's a specific moment/image, make it sing in 17 syllables.\"\n\nLet me rebuild this to be punchy and raw.Alright. Stripping out the explanatory bullshit. New haiku prompt\u2014less narrative, more *image*:\n\n---\n\n**Haiku**\n\nGive me 3. No preamble. No emotional setup. Just the moment. The image. The weird specificity that makes it hit different. Dark is fine. Unsettling is fine. Strange is required.\n\nOne prompt, three haikus, raw and no explanation.\n\n---\n\nBetter? Or do we need to go weirder?",
